Ultrasound and colour Doppler in infantile subglottic haemangioma.

Rossler L(1), Rothoeft T, Teig N, Koerner-Rettberg C, Deitmer T, Rieger CH, 
Hamelmann E.

Author information:
(1)Klinik für Kinder- und Jugendmedizin im St. Josef-Hospital, Ruhr-Universität 
Bochum, Bochum, Germany. l.rossler@klinikum-bochum.de

BACKGROUND: Subglottic haemangioma causes progressive and life-threatening 
stridor, typically manifesting at age 2-3 months. Standard diagnosis is by 
laryngoscopy. Larynx sonography is rarely used but allows assessment of the 
presence and extension of a mass that impinges on the subglottic airway. The 
additional use of colour Doppler enables demonstration of the vascular nature of 
such masses.
OBJECTIVE: To compare US and endoscopic findings in infants with subglottic 
haemangioma and to evaluate accuracy of US and colour Doppler imaging in this 
diagnosis.
MATERIALS AND METHODS: We report eight infants with subglottic haemangioma seen 
in our institution over the last decade. They presented with laryngeal stridor 
and were all investigated with both US and endoscopy. Six infants underwent 
colour Doppler sonography.
RESULTS: US and endoscopic findings showed excellent anatomical correlation in 
lateral subglottic haemangioma. Colour Doppler imaging was deemed helpful in 
four infants.
CONCLUSION: Larynx sonography with complementary colour Doppler imaging was 
non-invasive and helpful in the diagnosis of subglottic haemangioma.

