Perforated appendicitis in a septuagenarian.

Sanda RB(1), Seliem SI, Omar E, Ashraf S.

Author information:
(1)Department of Surgery, Drumheller Hospital, Drumheller AB, T0J 0Y1, Canada. 
robeesanda@yahoo.com

Appendicitis in the elderly is becoming an increasingly frequent clinical 
encounter due to the increased life expectancy in the human race over the last 
half-century. Appendicitis in this age group has, therefore, become relatively 
more common with an atypical presentation that incurs delay in diagnosis with 
attendant morbidity and mortality. We present a septuagenarian who presented 
atypically with a rapidly progressing feature of appendicitis that emphasizes 
the need for early operative intervention. In addition, the patient presented 
with other comorbidities that could detract from a diagnosis of appendicitis to 
the unwary.

